==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Saxon [[stunda]] (Dutch [[stonde]]), Old High German [[stunta]] (German [[Stunde]]), Old Norse ''stund'' (Swedish [[stund#Swedish|stund]]).

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/stʊnd/}}

===Noun===
'''stund''' ''f'' (plural '''[[stunda]]''' or '''[[stunde]]''')
# [[time]], [[while]]
# A period of time, an [[hour]]; specifically, a divison of the day probably equivalent to about three hours

====See also====
'''The eight stunda:'''
{{top2}}
*[[uhta|ūhta]] (3am-6am)
*[[morgen]] (6am-9am)
*[[undern]] (9am-12pm)
*[[middæg|middæġ]] (12pm-3pm)
{{mid2}}
*[[gelotendæg|ġelotendæġ]] (3pm-6pm)
*[[æfen]] (6pm-9pm)
*[[niht]] (9pm-12am)
*[[midniht]] (12am-3am)
{{bottom}}

